On Saturday, January 05, 2008, at 09:41AM, "Andy McKinley" <airhedz(-at-)gmail.com> wrote:

>The Bosch H4 conversion kit is not DOT approved for street use for a
>reason; the same reason people flash you.

If this was the case, people in Europe would be irritated by their own standard while driving identical vehicles but I don't think this isn't the case.

>The beam shape is not
>flattened at the top sufficiently to keep the light, even when on low
>beam, from shining into oncoming drivers' eyes. A recipe for a head-on
>collision. Yes, they are bright, but no brighter than the street legal
>Hella conversion available here:

I think this is just a case of improper aiming: there is an aiming specification for ECE lights and I'm sure more than a few buses have headlights out of alignment because the PO turned the wrong screw trying to undo the ring the holds the lamp in place.

I did a test a few years again pitting DOT against the European ECE standard as you can see in these photos:

http://www.ratwell.com/technical/BoschH4/PatternSealedlow.jpg
vs.
http://www.ratwell.com/technical/BoschH4/PatternH4Eurolow.jpg

The light is on the road, not in the on-coming driver's eyes.

